LOCATION:MAXWELL HALL - Room Number: Grand Hall
GEO:39.16705;-86.524718
SUMMARY:Emily Zazulia: "Music for the eyes? Rethinking 'Augenmusik'"
DESCRIPTION:Abstract: Late fifteenth-century music occasionally asks perf
 ormers to read its notation in unusual waysŌĆö from slowing down a melodi
 c line to turning it backwards or upside-down\, or even omitting certain 
 notes or rests. These visual elements are integral dimensions of the work
 's conceptual whole. Yet they have never sat easily with music scholars a
 nd critics for whom music is\, by definition\, that which reaches the ear
 s. In 1912\, Alfred Einstein gave this discomfort a name:Augenmusik\, mus
 ic for the eyes.Einstein's coinage\, it turns out\, says more about 1912 
 than about 1480. This paper traces the historiography of that term\, argu
 ing that each successive frameworkŌĆöfrom Einstein's formalist dismissal 
 to the modernist reclamation of the score as visual objectŌĆöhas projecte
 d its own assumptions about the relationship between the senses onto a re
 pertoire that operated by a different logic entirely. That logic\, I argu
 e\, was intellectual rather than sensory: for fifteenth-century musicians
 \, engaging with notation was not a deviation from aesthetic experience b
 ut a form of it\, a prized dimension of what it meant to encounter a piec
 e of music.Augenmusikearns its place\, finally\, as an admission: that no
 tation\, here\, was doing something the modern discipline had no other la
 nguage for.Emily Zazulia (https://music.berkeley.edu/people/emily-zazulia
 )is Associate Professor of Music at the University of California\, Berkel
 ey. Her first monographWhere Sight Meets Sound: The Poetics of Late-Medie
 val Music Writing(Oxford\, 2021) received the Early Music Award from the 
 American Musicological Society and the Emerging Scholar Book Award from t
 he Society for Music Theory. She has received other awards and fellowship
 s from the National Endowment for the Humanities\, the American Council o
 f Learned Societies\, the American Musicological Society\, the Medieval A
 cademy of America\, the Renaissance Society of America\, Harvard Universi
 ty's Villa I Tatti\, and the Hellman Foundation. Current major projects i
 nclude a monograph on popular song and ideas of the secular\, a co-edited
  volume on the composer Josquin des Prez\, and a digital project on Mappi
 ng the Musical Renaissance.Emily Zazulia's visit to Indiana University is
  made possible through generous support from the College of Arts and Scie
 nces\, the Department of Musicology\, and the Department of Music Theory.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><span data-contrast="none">Abstract</span
 ><span data-contrast="none">: Late fifteenth-century music occasionally a
 sks performers to read its notation in unusual waysŌĆö from slowing down 
 a melodic line to turning it backwards or upside-down\, or even omitting 
 certain notes or rests. These visual elements are integral dimensions of 
 the work's conceptual whole. Yet they have never sat easily with music sc
 holars and critics for whom music is\, by definition\, that which reaches
  the ears. In 1912\, Alfred Einstein gave this discomfort a name:</span><
 i><span data-contrast="none">Augenmusik</span></i><span data-contrast="no
 ne">\, music for the eyes.</span><span data-ccp-props="{}"></span></p><p>
 <span data-contrast="none">Einstein's coinage\, it turns out\, says more 
 about 1912 than about 1480. This paper traces the historiography of that 
 term\, arguing that each successive frameworkŌĆöfrom Einstein's formalist
  dismissal to the modernist reclamation of the score as visual objectŌĆöh
 as projected its own assumptions about the relationship between the sense
 s onto a repertoire that operated by a different logic entirely. That log
 ic\, I argue\, was intellectual rather than sensory: for fifteenth-centur
 y musicians\, engaging with notation was not a deviation from aesthetic e
 xperience but a form of it\, a prized dimension of what it meant to encou
 nter a piece of music.</span><i><span data-contrast="none">Augenmusik</sp
 an></i><span data-contrast="none">earns its place\, finally\, as an admis
 sion: that notation\, here\, was doing something the modern discipline ha
 d no other language for.</span><span data-ccp-props="{}"></span></p><p><s
 pan data-contrast="auto"><a class="external" href="https://music.berkeley
 .edu/people/emily-zazulia">Emily Zazulia</a></span><span data-contrast="a
 uto">is Associate Professor of Music at the University of California\, Be
 rkeley. Her first monograph</span><i><span data-contrast="auto">Where Sig
 ht Meets Sound: The Poetics of Late-Medieval Music Writing</span></i><spa
 n data-contrast="auto">(Oxford\, 2021) received the Early Music Award fro
 m the American Musicological Society and the Emerging Scholar Book Award 
 from the Society for Music Theory. She has received other awards and fell
 owships from the National Endowment for the Humanities\, the American Cou
 ncil of Learned Societies\, the American Musicological Society\, the Medi
 eval Academy of America\, the Renaissance Society of America\, Harvard Un
 iversity's Villa I Tatti\, and the Hellman Foundation. Current major proj
 ects include a monograph on popular song and ideas of the secular\, a co-
 edited volume on the composer Josquin des Prez\, and a digital project on
  Mapping the Musical Renaissance.</span><span data-ccp-props="{}"></span>
 </p><p><i><span data-contrast="none">Emily Zazulia's visit to Indiana Uni
 versity is made possible through generous support from the College of Art
 s and Sciences\, the Department of Musicology\, and the Department of Mus
 ic Theory.</span></i><span data-ccp-props="{}"></span></p>
