SUMMARY:Color Drawing and Painting Workshop
DESCRIPTION:Discover the joy of drawing in an inspiring setting! Begin by
  sketching directly from artwork in the collection to sharpen your eye an
 d strengthen your skills. Then\, move into the studio to learn about colo
 r theory and add color to your artwork.Strengthen fundamental drawing ski
 lls  Explore color theory in action  Experiment with color media  Expand 
 your creative expression in a hands-on way  Reserve your spot. If this pa
 ge says\, "Registration has closed" that means the waitlist is full.Suppl
 iesBring your favorite drawing pencil (e.g. 4B)\, a sketchbook or drawing
  paper\, and a phone or device to photograph artwork (without flash) as w
 e sketch. Additional supplies are provided.  Know Before You GoArrive ear
 ly to find parking\, check in\, and get your drawing supplies ready.  At 
 1:55 p.m. any unclaimed reservations will be released to guests who are s
 tanding by waiting for a spot.  Where to find us\, where to park\, access
 ibility\, and museum guidelines (https://artmuseum.indiana.edu/visit/your
 -visit.html).  This workshop is recommended for ages 12 and up. Anyone un
 der 18\, who is not an IU student\, must be accompanied by an adult.  Whe
 n You ArriveCheck in with Guest Services at the information desk on the f
 irst floor\, even if you come often and even if you are late. We apprecia
 te having an accurate attendance count.  Store all backpacks and large ba
 gs before entering the galleries. A small handbag may be carried at your 
 side.  Get your supplies ready. Attach an 18x24" piece of newsprint to a 
 drawing board.  Cancellations  This workshop often has a waitlist. Please
  use the cancellation link included with your confirmation email if your 
 plans change.About the Instructor  John Cheek has taught credit and non-c
 redit classes for eight years in portrait painting\, landscape painting\,
  palette knife painting\, life drawing\, beginning drawing\, and advanced
  drawing\, as well as in design. He volunteers his time and expertise to 
 facilitate drawing workshops at the Eskenazi Museum of Art.
